........................................................................................................................................................vi Aims and objectives ......................................................................................................................................................1 Audience and partners ..................................................................................................................................................2 Geography and diversity ...............................................................................................................................................2 Sources ............................................................................................................................................................................4 Summary.........................................................................................................................................................................4 Terminology ..................................................................................................................................................................11 Recommendations ......................................................................................................................................................12 Acknowledgements The development of Leave no one behind: Advancing social, economic, cultural and political inclusion of LGBTI people in Asia and the Pacific benefited from an in-depth and consultative process with contributions from many individuals, government and human rights experts, community-based organizations and institutions. Many played a critical role by participating and providing personal stories during eight Being LGBTI in Asia national dialogues and the \u2018Regional Dialogue on LGBTI Human Rights and Health in Asia-Pacific\u2019 held from 25\u201327 February 2015. This report would not have been possible without these contributions. This report was informed by the Being LGBTI in Asia: Regional Overview Report on the National Consultations Phase 1 authored by Andy Quan; the Analysis of Existing Evidence Related to SOGI issues and LGBTI Rights in Asia authored by Emma Day; and the Report of the Regional Dialogue on LGBTI Human Rights and Health in Asia-Pacific authored by John Godwin. Our thanks and special gratitude to John Godwin for his invaluable contributions as the author of this report. Edmund Settle, Policy Advisor, United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) Bangkok Regional Hub managed the development of the report. Thanks are also due to Andy Quan for his editing of the final draft of the report. The contributions of the following government and human rights experts who reviewed drafts are gratefully acknowledged: Hon. Louisa Wall, Member of Parliament, New Zealand; Hon. Oyungerel Tsedevdamba, Member of Parliament, Mongolia; Professor Vitit Muntarbhorn, Professor of Law, Chulalongkorn University, Thailand; and, Nurul Malim, Deputy Secretary, Policy, Law and Complaints Group, SUHAKAM (Human Rights Commission of Malaysia). The report benefited from excellent contributions from the following community experts: Shale Ahmed, Bangladesh; Ashok Row Kavi, Vivek Divan and Kajal Bharadwaj, India; D\u00e9d\u00e9 Oetomo, Indonesia; Amanda Hill and Jack Byrne, New Zealand; Qasim Iqbal, Muhammad Osama and Dr Muhammad Moiz, Pakistan; and Ging Cristobal, Philippines. The report profited greatly from the valuable advice and review from the following UN offices: UNDP Bangkok Regional Hub: Nadia Rasheed, Ian Mungall, Nicholas Booth, Kazuyuki Uji, Katri Kivioja, Ernest Noronha, Jensen Byrne and Tivea Koam.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b82b0da7-5707-4790-9cdd-ba245d10c5f0": {"__data__": {"id_": "b82b0da7-5707-4790-9cdd-ba245d