p of Out Leadership and Pink Dot, live tweeting was conducted throughout the three-day event using the hashtag. Tweeting was done from both the @beinglgbti and @OutLeadership accounts. Global LGBTI partners, influencers, organizations and individuals were tagged and mentioned for potential retweets. \u2022 Videos capturing the highlights of the dialogue and opening remarks were produced and widely shared. \u2022 Photographs for the dialogue were published in an album on the Being LGBT in Asia Flickr account. Report of the Regional Dialogue on LGBTI Human Rights and Health in Asia-Pacific 71 Social media results \u2022 Posts from the Being LGBT in Asia Facebook page appeared over 70,000 times on Facebook newsfeeds. \u2022 Through our Being LGBT in Asia Twitter following of about 3,000, our tweets reached 300,000 accounts in our Twitter network. \u2022 Most impressively, our hashtag #BeingLGBTI reached almost 6 million unique people on Twitter. United Nations Development Programme Bangkok Regional Hub 3rd Floor United Nations Service Building Rajdamnern Nok Avenue, Bangkok 10200 Thailand Tel: +66 (0)2 304 9100 Fax: +66 (0)2 280 2700 http://asia-pacific.undp.org", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c1ffcaf9-9f0b-4489-8dd6-3ede69a5c642": {"__data__": {"id_": "c1ffcaf9-9f0b-4489-8dd6-3ede69a5c642", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/assessing-relationship-between-natural-hazards-and-poverty-conceptual-and-methodological-proposal", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Assessing the Relationship between Natural Hazards and Poverty \u2013 A Conceptual and Methodological Proposal", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/assessing-relationship-between-natural-hazards-and-poverty-conceptual-and-methodological-proposal", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ec66078e223679c0f7274e24180a9a829bbe390b212c109de85784491c567b71"}, "3": {"node_id": "dd3acf67-319e-4a6b-919a-f532a9f8456c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/assessing-relationship-between-natural-hazards-and-poverty-conceptual-and-methodological-proposal", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d4cb1fc338962961adaf4905f73397e93c6fef4c5856c65d4a751e9ee749bb4c"}}, "hash": "68335a3afe3528e2d2c6bda96d8d0ecf79c092d8d2308e0d87782afccdc486fa", "text": "Regional Programme on Capacity Building for Sustainable Recovery and Risk Reduction Assessing the Relationship between Natural Hazards and Poverty A Conceptual and Methodological Proposal Assessing the Relationship between Natural Hazards and Poverty A Conceptual and Methodological Proposal United Nations Development Programme Regional Programme on Capacity Building for Sustainable Recovery and Risk Reduction Assessing the Relationship between Natural Hazards and Poverty: A Conceptual and Methodological Proposal Authors: Alejandro de la Fuente, Luis Felipe L\u00f3pez-Calva and Aromar Revi The analysis, opinions and policy recommendations contained in this publication do not necessarily reflect the views of UNDP. United Nations Development Programme Regional Centre in Bangkok UN Service Building Rajdamnern Nok Avenue Bangkok 10200 Thailand http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th Copyright \u00a9 UNDP 2009 ISBN: 978-974-680-255-0 Cover photos: \u00a9Greenpeace/Sataporn, iStock, UNDP, World Bank Design and Layout: In\u00eds Communication \u2013 www.inis.ie Printed in Thailand Contents 1 Motivation and Objectives 1 1.1 Policy and development context 1 1.2 Methodological considerations 1 1.3 Outline of methodological proposal 2 2 Hypothesis 4 3 Conceptual Framework 5 3.1 Access to and ownership of assets 5 3.2 Asset transformation 5 3.3 Entitlements into welfare outcomes 6 3.4 Hazard effects on poverty 6 3.5 A dynamic reconfiguration: Poverty effects on the propensity to suffer hazard losses 7 4 Statistical and Econometric Methods 10 4.1 Static poverty analysis \u2013 Hypothesis #1 10 4.2 Poverty trends analysis \u2013 Hypothesis #2 14 4.3 Poverty micro-dynamics \u2013 Hypothesis #2 16 5 Conclusion 24 Annex I \u2013 Concepts and Definitions 25 1.1 Hazard 25 1.2 Poverty 26 1.3 Assets 27 Annex II \u2013 Data Sources 28 2.1 Hazard data 28 2.2 Asset data 31 2.3 Welfare outcomes data 34 2.4 Types of household surveys available 36 Annex III \u2013 Databases of Country Studies 38 Risk\u2013Poverty data availability for Latin American case studies 38 Risk\u2013Poverty data availability for Asian case studies 40 References 41 iv List of Boxes, Figures and Tables Box 1: Creating a transition matrix 17 Box 2: Asset poverty transitions 19 Figure 1: Assets, natural disasters and poverty: Suggested causalities 8 Table 1: Proposed quantitative approaches to hazard-poverty analysis 11 Table 2: Selected characteristics in a subsample of rural households in Ethiopia, 1989\u20131994 18 Table 3: The impact of shocks in 1999\u20132004 on poverty in rural Ethiopia in 2004 23 Table 4: Asset data needs at household, community and extra-community level 33 Table 5: Poverty indicators proposed for analysis 35 1 Motivation and Objectives 1.1 Policy and development context The International Strategy for Disaster Reduction (ISDR) secretariat and the World Bank with the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) and other partners are currently coordinating the preparation of the ISDR system\u2019s first biennial Global Assessment Report on Disaster Risk Reduction (GAR) (ISDR, 2009). The GAR will fulfill three main objectives: \u2022\ufffd It is expected that the report will establish itself as a credible and widely accepted reference point for information on global hazard patterns and trends. \u2022\ufffd It will strengthen the ISDR system\u2019s capacity for planning and joint programming at all levels by providing a global review of achievements and gaps in hazard risk reduction from national, regional and thematic reporting. \u2022\ufffd Each issue of the GAR will increase understanding and awareness of the mutually supportive relationship between development and hazard risk reduction, through an in- depth analysis of key linkages and interfaces between hazards and a development theme of global concern. Related to the third point, a series of major developments at both the international and national level have reasserted the need to understand and reduce poor people\u2019s exposure to external and largely uncontrollable climatic or geological hazards that reinforce the poor\u2019s sense of ill-being and exacerbate their material poverty. The findings from worldwide consultations with the poor carried out by the World Bank in preparation for its report on Attacking Poverty (World Bank, 2000), UNDP\u2019s recognition of the mutual links between disasters and development (UNDP, 2004) and the UK Department for International Development\u2019s explication of the links between development and disasters in view of the long-term impacts on poverty trends (DFID, 2004), have helped to prioritize policy attention on the links between poverty and disaster risk over the past years.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dd3acf67-319e-4a6b-919a-f532a9f8456c": {"__data__": {"id_": "dd3acf67-319e-4a6b-919a-f532a9f8456c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/assessing-relationship-between-natural-hazards-and-poverty-conceptual-and-methodological-proposal", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Assessing the Relationship between Natural Hazards and Poverty \u2013 A Conceptual and Methodological Proposal", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/assessing-relationship-between-natural-hazards-and-poverty-conceptual-and-methodological-proposal", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ec66078e223679c0f7274e24180a9a829bbe390b212c109de85784491c567b71"}, "2": {"node_id": "c1ffcaf9-9f0b-4489-8dd6-3ede69a5c642", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/assessing-relationship-between-natural-hazards-and-poverty-conceptual-and-methodological-proposal", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "68335a3afe3528e2d2c6bda96d8d0ecf79c092d8d2308e0d87782afccdc486fa"}}, "hash": "d4cb1fc338962961adaf4905f73397e93c6fef4c5856c65d4a751e9ee749bb4c", "text": "Significant social and economic consequences of major recent natural hazards in different parts of the world have reiterated the need to place hazard concerns higher on the global poverty agenda. In parallel, the mounting evidence that global climate change is catapulting the recurrence and virulence of climatic hazards in vast parts of the world, such as droughts and floods, has reinforced the sense of urgency to address this matter. In view of these significant developments over past years and the lack of empirical research on", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metad